  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">AbleChildAfrica - Organisational Development Grant 2012</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Originally founded as the Uganda Society for Disabled Children (USDC), ACA have over 25 years&apos; experience working in East Africa.  Since the end of their investment grant, ACA have gone through a number of significant changes, including the departure of their Director. Historically, ACA&apos;s partnerships have developed through opportunities rather than identified strategic priorities and their approach to capacity building has been sporadic. They now want to focus on developing a clearer partnership model which will enable their approach to be more formalised and strategic. ACA are committed to ensuring this formalisation of partnerships is not at the expense of their partner-centric approach. Greater clarity about the purpose of partnership and the level of support ACA can offer will allow greater transparency with partners and enable ACA to be more focused in their interventions. ACA developed this grant application based on their recent strategic review process, which reaffirmed their commitment to working in partnership with organisations in Africa. The strategy articulates a new focus on independently contributing to and influencing inclusive development through advocacy and training of other INGOs so that they address disability issues more effectively in their own work. They will to use this OD grant to set in motion their new strategy which was developed through an OD grant from CR last year (cycle 5). In particular, they will develop a partnership model/ process, develop their M&amp;E framework, develop an advocacy strategy and develop a public fundraising strategy. This work will be conducted by external consultants and ACA staff. Training has been incorporated for staff to ensure the appropriate skill level within the organisation to continue this work and provision is made for the Trustees to reflect on the processes through external facilitation.</narrative>
  </description>
